    "recap_headline": "North Carolina State University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "Raleigh, N. C.-\nHeath Andrews\npitched seven strong innings, and No. 10 NC State used a three- run fifth inning to secure its first ACC series of the season with a 5-1 victory over Boston College on Sunday afternoon at the Doak. It was the fourth straight series win over Boston College in Raleigh.\nTwelve days had passed since Andrews (2-0) took the mound after starting against Coastal Carolina on March 3 rd. Andrews didn't miss a beat, allowing just one unearned run on seven hits, with one walk and four strikeouts.\nAll three starting pitchers for NC State (16-4, 2-1) pitched seven innings this weekend and combined to allow only five runs (four earned). Andrews' s seven innings tied his career high.\nCooper Consiglio\n(1) earned his first career save after coming on and finishing what Andrews started. Consiglio pitched two innings, permitting just one hit and striking out three.\nThe Eagles (11-8, 3-3) were 0- for- 6 with runners in scoring position and 0-for- 13 with a runner on base. Their only run came in the top of the third after a throwing error by NC State allowed the runner on first to score.\nIn a 1-1 game, in the bottom of the fifth, back- to- back walks by\nSherman Johnson\nand\nDrew Lanphere\nstarted the inning, and a bunt single from\nRett Johnson\nloaded the bases with no outs.\nMikey Ryan\n, in a 2-2 count, hit a double to left field to drive in two runs and put the Pack ahead, and Brayden Frassman added a third run with an RBI single to make it 4-1.\nChris McHugh\nwent 2- for- 3 with a double and an RBI, while Johnson finished 2- for- 3, ending the three- game series with a .778 batting average, seven hits, three runs scored, one RBI, two walks, and a stolen base.\nAndrews fought out of multiple jams all afternoon, leaving runners in scoring position in the fifth and seventh innings.\nMcHugh tied the game in the bottom of the fourth with a sacrifice fly. Coming into the weekend, the Pack led the ACC and was second in the nation in sacrifice flies, with 21 on the season after Sunday's game.\nSunday's game concludes the Wolfpack's 18-game homestand as they prepare to hit the road for the first true road test of the season against UNCW in Wilmington on Tuesday, March 17th at 6 p. m."
  },
